1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:06,830
In this video, we are going to learn one of two fundamental design patterns of microservice architecture,

2
00:00:06,830 --> 00:00:09,950
which is the database per service pattern.

3
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:16,490
One of the core characteristic of the microservice architecture is the loosely coupling services.

4
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:20,930
For that reason, every service should have its own database.

5
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:24,830
It can be a polyglot persistence among the microservices.

6
00:00:26,870 --> 00:00:29,630
Let's think about our e-commerce application.

7
00:00:29,630 --> 00:00:37,460
We will have product shopping cart and ordering microservices that each services data in their own database.

8
00:00:37,460 --> 00:00:41,300
And any changes to one database don't impact the other.

9
00:00:41,300 --> 00:00:42,320
Microservices.

10
00:00:45,650 --> 00:00:50,240
The services database can't be accessed directly by other microservices.

11
00:00:50,270 --> 00:00:55,820
Each services persistent data can only be accessed via Rest APIs.

12
00:00:57,960 --> 00:00:59,820
So database per service.

13
00:00:59,820 --> 00:01:07,020
Microservice provides many benefits, especially for evolve rapidly and support massive scale systems.

14
00:01:07,050 --> 00:01:10,770
Let's talk about the benefits of database per service pattern.

15
00:01:11,610 --> 00:01:18,780
The first benefit is data schema changes made easy without impacting other microservices, and each

16
00:01:18,780 --> 00:01:21,390
database can scale independently.

17
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:27,090
Microservices domain data is encapsulated within the microservices itself.

18
00:01:28,080 --> 00:01:33,420
If one of the database server is down, this will not affect the other services.

19
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:41,220
Also, polyglot data persistence gives ability to select the best optimized storage needs as per the

20
00:01:41,220 --> 00:01:42,210
microservices.

21
00:01:44,460 --> 00:01:49,650
So if you see the image on the slide, that is the example of microservice architecture of e-commerce

22
00:01:49,650 --> 00:01:50,490
application.

23
00:01:50,490 --> 00:01:58,620
We will have product shopping cart and ordering microservices that each services data in their own database.

24
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:06,240
The first microservice is product microservices, the product microservice using NoSQL document database

25
00:02:06,240 --> 00:02:12,990
for storing catalog related data, which is storing Json objects to accommodate high volume of read

26
00:02:12,990 --> 00:02:13,920
operations.

27
00:02:15,680 --> 00:02:18,200
And the second microservice is shopping cart.

28
00:02:18,230 --> 00:02:25,100
The shopping cart microservice using a distributed cache that supports it is simple key value data store.

29
00:02:25,970 --> 00:02:28,850
And the last microservice is ordering microservices.

30
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:35,270
The ordering microservice using a relational database to accommodate to reach relational structure of

31
00:02:35,270 --> 00:02:36,740
its underlying data.

